      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c6ac066773a12d13",
      "text": "A simple binary categorization into male and female does not do justice to the phenotypical reality of individuals."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ffe2fa877b26cb1b",
      "text": "Sex researchers and psychologists have known this for a long time, which is why the term \"[[Gender]]\" was introduced as an auxiliary construct for perceived or social gender identity, which is contrasted with biological sex determination. However, biological gender development should also be seen as an overall process that should not be divided into categories – i.e. not even into extended gender categories."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "db1811edee6c0be8",
      "text": "Each individual must be seen for themselves, and each individual should therefore be allowed to find their own role in the continuous spectrum of distributions. No individual should feel pressured to conform to the social norm of a category. This is where the apparent binary of gender dissolves into an illusion. Individuals should not be reduced to their sex cells; the reality of evolutionary and developmental biology is much more complex."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1cc81d2c568db08c",
      "text": "Against this background, the progress that is to be achieved with the new law on sexual self-determination is actually a step backwards. Instead of completely abolishing the official registration of gender categories, freedom of choice is being introduced. However, this is actually a compulsion to choose, because ultimately everyone has to ask themselves at some point which category they belong to."
